ent Still Pervasive -- t78. A Momentous Prayer Meeting -- t79. England for the King -- t80. The Battle of Preston -- t81. Pride's Purge -- t82. A Constitutional Revolution -- t83. The Trial of Charles I -- t84. Execution of the King -- t85. Milton Writes The Tenure -- t86. Milton as Latin Secretary -- t87. Milton's Reply to the Great Salmasius -- t88. The Battle of Dunbar -- t89. The Battle of Worcester -- t90. Milton and Mercurius Politicus -- t91. Milton's Growing Renown -- t92. Milton in Total Darkness -- tMilton Under the Protectorate -- t93. Dissolution of the Rump -- t94. Milton's Second Defence -- t95. Milton on the Vaudois Massacres -- t96. The Death of Cromwell -- t97. Dilemma of Richard Cromwell -- t98. Bridget Cromwell -- t99. For the Good Old Cause: Milton's Last Stand -- tMilton in the Restoration -- t100. Milton Wanted by the King -- t101. Milton Arrested and Jailed -- t102. How Did Milton Escape? -- t103. The "Incomparable Lady Ranelagh" -- t104. Abuse of Commonwealth Heroes -- t105. Hugh Peters on the Scaffold -- t106. The Execution of Sir Henry Vane -- t107. The Plague in London: 1665 -- t108. Milton at Chalfont St. Giles -- t109. Friends in the Jordans Churchyard -- t110. Milton Completes Paradise Lost -- t111. Milton and Raphael's Adam and Eve -- t112. Milton and the Tawny Lion -- t113. The Creation of Eve -- t114. Adam and Eve Expelled from Paradise -- t115. The Great Fire of London: 1666 -- t116. The Publication of Paradise Lost -- t117. The Reception of Paradise Lost -- t118. The Publication of Paradise Regained and Samson -- t119. The Last Months of Milton's Life -- tChronology of Main Events -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn narrative and some 120 pictures, Don M. Wolfe traces Milton's life in the context of the public events and common scenes of his time. His illustrations and vignettes, supported by passages from the history of the period as well as the poet's own writings, bring to life the people, politics, and society of seventeenth-century England: maidens carrying fresh cream and cheese on their heads, men with hats and caps to sell; the Long Parliament of 1640; Charles I's summary trial and execution; Cromwell's Protectorate; the London Plague of 1665 and the Great Fire of 1666; the publication of Paradise Lost.The principal figure is, of course, John Milton, seen first as a boy of ten, sober and confident, even "then a poet." He is seen also as a traveler to the continent in 1638-1639, when he filled his mind with scenes and places that he would use in Paradise Lost: the sulphuric Phlegraean Fields outside Naples; Galileo, the "Tuscan artist" with optic glass. Milton the revolutionary is described, the libertarian pamphleteer whose passionate cry that every man had the right "to know, to utter, to argue freely" was realized around the campfires of the New Model Army. Throughout, Milton is depicted also as the poet aspiring to "leave something so written to aftertimes, as they should not willingly let it die"—his creative genius coming forth at last in Paradise Lost and his final major work, Samson Agonistes.Originally published in 1971.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPoets, EnglishxHomes and hauntszEn